5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; vertical-align:middle; width:78pt"><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:center; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">2%</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; vertical-align:middle; width:85.05pt"><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:center; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">2%</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; vertical-align:middle; width:85.05pt"><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:center; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">2%</span></p></td></tr></table><p style="line-height:1pt; margin:0pt 3.6pt 27.05pt 9pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.8pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11.5pt; letter-spacing:0.5pt">iv)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">We give an external perspective:</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:114%; margin:9pt 0pt 0pt 7.2pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">Often, we 'shine a light' into areas that are obscured from the view of providers. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">Usually, they accept our findings, acknowledge their failings, and put them right. Even when they may be displeased by the discovery that their systems or </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">management procedures are not as good as they thought they were providers still </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">tend to accept our de</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">cisions recognising that they are fair and un-biased and that the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">Ombudsman has a unique perspective on the way their organisations operate in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">practice.</span></p><p style="margin:9pt 0pt 0pt 10.8pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11.5pt; letter-spacing:0.5pt">v)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">We make </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:0.05pt">'gratis' </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">recommendations:</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:114%; margin:12.6pt 14.4pt 0pt 7.2pt; orphans:0; text-indent:3.6pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">Even where we do not make a finding of service failure or maladminist</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">ration we </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">sometimes make suggestions to providers for them to consider as part of their customer care and service provision. How they deal with those suggestions is a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">matter for them but we consider this to be another contribution to the value that we </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">can </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">add to providers and their residents to enrich service provision and customer </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">care.</span></p><p style="margin:10.8pt 0pt 0pt 10.8pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11.5pt; letter-spacing:0.5pt">vi)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">We identify service failure:</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:114%; margin:10.8pt 14.4pt 0pt 7.2pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">From April 2013 and the operation of the new Scheme, I have been able to make </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">findings not only of maladministration but also service failure. A finding of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">maladministration or, indeed, severe maladministration will still be available to and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">will be made in appropriate circumstances but extending the spectrum of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">maladministration wi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">ll </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">enable findings that would not have merited the strength of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">criticism evoked by the concept of 'maladministration'. Feedback we have received </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">from providers and other </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">stakeholders indicates that providers are more likely to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">react with good grace to, and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt"> residents will, accordingly, benefit from, such findings </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">which can be expressed in more conciliatory and positive terms.</span></p><p style="margin:10.8pt 0pt 0pt 10.8pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11.5pt; letter-spacing:0.5pt">vii)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">We encourage local solutions:</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:114%; margin:10.8pt 14.4pt 0pt 7.2pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">I now have the power to authorise the drafting of many more orders and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">recommendations in terms that wil</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">l set out the presenting issues and then require </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">providers to design appropriate remedial actions. Again, feedback from providers </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">and other stakeholders during the consultation process that preceded formal </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">approval of my new Scheme, indicated that provider</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">s would more likely to be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">encouraged to take responsibility for resolving disputes and be more likely to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">produce an outcome that suits local conditions and meets the particular needs of residents especially if providers work with tenant scrutiny panels. We</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt"> are gathering </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">data against which we shall test these assumptions.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:114%; margin:10.8pt 14.4pt 0pt 10.8pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11.5pt; letter-spacing:0.5pt">viii)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">Under the terms of my Scheme, providers are expected to comply with my </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">determinations. If they do not, I have the power to:</span></p><p style="margin:9pt 18pt 0pt 46.8pt; orphans:0; text-indent:-18pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.7pt">a)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">Require them to report to me on compliance with a determination in such a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">way and at such a time as I may specify;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 7.2pt 0pt 46.8pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.7pt">b)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">Report them to any appropriate regulatory agency and/or, in accordance with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">the policy o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">f localism and co-regulation as expressed in the Localism Act, the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">boards, committees, or tenant scrutiny panels of providers;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 10.8pt 0pt 46.8pt; orphans:0; text-indent:-18pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.7pt">c)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">Order them to publish that they have failed to comply, in such a way as I see fit;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 7.2pt 0pt 46.8pt; orphans:0; text-indent:-18pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.7pt">d)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">Publish the facts and circumstances of non-compliance naming the providers </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">in my annual report or elsewhere.</span></p><p style="margin:14.4pt 0pt 0pt 3.6pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">ix)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">We share our learning:</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:114%; margin:9pt 3.6pt 0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">An important objective of my Service has always been to share lessons learnt not </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">only with landlords but also with other</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">s with an interest in the outcomes of our core </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">process. Traditionally, we have done this by publishing reports, speaking at </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">conferences and seminars, and providing training for Board members, front-line staff, and tenants. Landlords, in particular, have fe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">d back to us that these initiatives have </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">helped them to change and to design policies and practices in respect of complaint-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">handling in particular and wider customer service in general. Our historical shared-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">learning </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">inter-actions with providers and residents were so well-valued and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">respected that we were frequently approached by landlords and landlord and tenant </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">bodies to deliver it for them by special request.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:114%; margin:10.8pt 7.2pt 0pt 3.6pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">To deliver our current vision and mission we intend to wo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">rk with landlords and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">tenants to resolve disputes that come to us impartially using processes that are fair, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">evidence-based, and free of bias and prejudice. These principles of dispute </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">resolution will be,the basis of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">our work with landlords, tenants, MPs, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">councillors, and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">tenant panels. We are developing an extended set of dispute resolution principles </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">which will be augmented by complementary learning media. Working with all </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">interested parties, we aim to achieve accessible dispute resolution that will be of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">benefit to both landlords and tenants and encourage landlords to use these </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">outcomes to improve the services they provide.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:90%; margin:12.6pt 0pt 0pt 3.6pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:0.05pt">Governance:</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:114%; margin:9pt 7.2pt 0pt 3.6pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">The Housing Act 1996 (Sch. 2., para.10) provides for the Ombudsman's Scheme to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">be administered by a body corporate or by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">a corporation sole. Until 1 April 2013 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">there was a body corporate, IHO Limited, a company limited by guarantee and not </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">trading for profit which, in 2006, was designated as an eNDPB. The Board </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">comprised equal numbers of tenants, landlords, and independents </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">(the 'constituency </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">model'). The Secretary of State made an order establishing The Housing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">Ombudsman as a corporation sole. As Ombudsman, Chief Executive, and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">Accounting Officer, I am supported</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt"> by an Audit and Risk Committee. In accordance </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">with an express provision in the Scheme I may set up a Panel of Advisors but such a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">group is not part of the governance of the corporation sole and advises me </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">personally.</span></p><p style="margin:7.2pt 0pt 0pt 7.2pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">The principal reasons for changes in g</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">overnance were:</span></p><p style="margin:14.4pt 46.8pt 0pt 50.4pt; orphans:0; text-indent:-21.6pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.35pt"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">To support my independence as Ombudsman in the discharge of my </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">statutory function;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 50.4pt; orphans:0; text-indent:-21.6pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.35pt"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">To remove 'double governance';</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 28.8pt 0pt 50.4pt; orphans:0; text-indent:-21.6pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.35pt"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">To reduce the costs (direct and indirect) of servicing two full governance </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">structures;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 25.2pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.35pt"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">To remove the potential for conflict </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">arising from my three roles;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 25.2pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.35pt"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">The extension of jurisdiction under the Localism Act 2011;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 25.2pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.35pt"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">To reflect my future status as an office holder not an employee.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:14.4pt 180pt 0pt 7.2pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">I turn now to the specific points raised in your letter. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:0.05pt; text-decoration:underline">Harmonisation of Ombudsman Schemes </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:82%; margin:10.8pt 0pt 0pt 7.2pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:0.05pt">Ease of ac</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:0.05pt">cess:</span></p><p style="margin:10.8pt 7.2pt 0pt 3.6pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">Two of the primary outcomes of our mission and vision are that tenants and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">landlords have increased trust in dispute resolution and designated persons are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">playing their part in resolving disputes fairly. It is important to understand that, for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">us, th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">e 'increased trust' refers broadly to dispute resolution in rented housing that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">may be taking place locally between landlords and tenants or by designated persons as well as when it is escalated to me.</span></p><p style="margin:12.6pt 7.2pt 0pt 3.6pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">Achievem</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">ent of our strategic intent will deliver better access to dispute resolution for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">residents.</span></p><p style="margin:10.8pt 7.2pt 0pt 3.6pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">Many providers, especially since the coming into force of the Localism Act, have </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">reduced </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">their ICPs to two stages and many do not explicitly refer to 'stages' in an</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt"> attempt to resolve complaints and disputes without raising an expectation that all </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">`stages' must be completed before resolution may be had. Such providers share with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">us the importance of early, local, appropriate, and proportionate dispute resolution.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:84%; margin:14.4pt 0pt 0pt 3.6pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:0.05pt">Con</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:0.05pt">fusion:</span></p><p style="margin:14.4pt 7.2pt 0pt 3.6pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">My recent experience is that confusion about the ways in which people in my </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">jurisdiction can complain has been caused by two principal factors. The first is the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">clumsy, complex, and clunky drafting of section 180 of the Localism Act. When I </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">asked a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt"> leading Housing Law QC for advice on certain aspects of this section one of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">his observations was that "it is clear that it is unclear". If this is the opinion of a QC </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">landlords and tenants can be forgiven if they too are confused and probably explains why</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt"> myths such as that of the "8-week rule" occur.</span></p><p style="margin:10.8pt 10.8pt 0pt 3.6pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">Linked to this is the complete lack of communication by government of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">consequences of legislation such as section 180 to people who will be affected by it.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 7.2pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">We are all committed to achieving cost effectiveness and good value for money in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">these times of economic challenge and austerity but there is a strong case for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">certain, especially low-cost, exceptions. My Service does not have the resources to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">mount far-reaching communication exercises. Even if we did, we must seek an </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">exemption from DCLG to spend money from our budget on, for instance, leaflets for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">tenants. Recently, for example, I put up a business case to spend £6,000 on such </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">leaflets but, in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">line with Francis Maude's decrees concerning spending on marketing, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">promotion, and communication, was eventually granted an exemption to spend £4,000.</span></p><p style="margin:9pt 10.8pt 0pt 3.6pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:3.6pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">Given these systemic limitations on our ability to inform, our strategic approach is to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">work with others </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:0.05pt">(e.g. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">landlords, trade bodies, and others) to use their networks and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">resources to reach our customers.</span></p><p style="margin:14.4pt 0pt 0pt 3.6pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:0.05pt">Fitting alongside others:</span></p><p style="margin:14.4pt 7.2pt 0pt 3.6pt; orphans:0; text-indent:3.6pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">In terms of consultation and collaborative working the Localism Act adds the Housing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">Ombudsman to the list of bodies with whom </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">the Local Government Ombudsmen (LGO) may consult during the course of their investigations. It also provides that if, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">at any stage in the course of conducting an investigation, I form the opinion that the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">complaint relates partly to a matter which could be</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt"> the subject of an investigation by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">the LGO, I must consult with the appropriate 'Commissioner' about the complaint </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">and, if I consider it necessary, inform the complainant of the steps necessary to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">initiate a complaint with the LGO.</span></p><p style="margin:12.6pt 7.2pt 0pt 3.6pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">Provision is also made </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">to enable me and the LGO to carry out joint investigations. In </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">particular, if at any stage in the course of conducting an investigation I form the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">opinion that the complaint relates partly to a matter within the jurisdiction of the LGO, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:0.05pt">I </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">may conduct an investigation jointly with the LGO provided I have first obtained the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">consent of the complainant or the complainant's representative. Moreover, if I form the opinion that a complaint which is being investigated by the LGO relates partly to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt"> matter within my jurisdiction, I may conduct an investigation jointly with the LGO </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">and we may make joint reports so long as we distinguish my determinations from </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">other findings or </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">recommendations.</span></p><p style="margin:14.4pt 7.2pt 0pt 3.6pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">I am currently talking to the LGO about a memorandum of un</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">derstanding (MOU) that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">will help us provide a seamless, high quality service to our respective customers for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">those occasions, should they ever occur, when we might conduct joint investigations. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">There have not been any since 1 April 2013.</span></p><p style="margin:12.6pt 32.4pt 0pt 3.6pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">We do not have an </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">MOU with the PHSO. To my knowledge we have not had a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">single case in which our jurisdictions have ever overlapped although sometimes </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">people have contacted the PHSO about a matter within my jurisdiction and have </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">been referred by them to me.</span></p><p style="margin:14.4pt 0pt 0pt 3.6pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:0.05pt">Sharing good prac</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:0.05pt">tice with other Ombudsmen:</span></p><p style="margin:10.8pt 21.6pt 0pt 3.6pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">My colleagues and I attend conferences and special interest groups arranged and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">supported by the Ombudsman Association. Although my predecessor decided to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">stop attending meetings of the Public Sector Ombudsmen Group because he, l</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">ike</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">me, considered the Housing Ombudsman to be, predominantly, a private sector ombudsman, I decided to accept Sir Tony Redmond's invitation to attend meetings of the group because I took the view that any opportunity to mix with other </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">ombudsmen to share good </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">practice, challenges, mutual concerns and interests, new </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">developments, and emerging trends was of benefit to my Service.</span></p><p style="margin:10.8pt 14.4pt 0pt 3.6pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">My colleagues and I also meet other ombudsman and their colleagues at different </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">levels for different purposes. In recent months, for ex</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">ample, I have had meetings with The Property Ombudsman, the Ombudsman (Property), the Pensions Ombudsman and the CEO of The Dispute Service. Colleagues have visited, for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">example, the Legal Ombudsman to share concerns and ambitions concerning data </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">collectio</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">n and processing for accountability, improved organisational performance, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">and better customer service.</span></p><p style="margin:14.4pt 0pt 0pt 3.6pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:0.05pt">Single access point:</span></p><p style="margin:12.6pt 10.8pt 0pt 3.6pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">I am instinctively but cautiously drawn to this concept by the obvious benefits </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">especially to customers if it could be organised eff</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">ectively and efficiently. During the course of my nearly 13 years as an ombudsman I have been to many meetings in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">different </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:0.05pt">fora </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">to discuss the implementation of a 'single portal'. It remains, however, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">something of the 'holy grail' of ombudsmanry.</span></p><p style="margin:12.6pt 0pt 0pt 3.6pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">My conce</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">rns are:</span></p><p style="margin:14.4pt 0pt 0pt 21.6pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.35pt"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">Will it deliver my strategic aims and their primary outcomes?</span></p><p style="margin:1.8pt 0pt 0pt 21.6pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.35pt"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">How is it going to be paid for?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 21.6pt 0pt 43.2pt; orphans:0; text-indent:-21.6pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.35pt"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">Will that be more expensive than my present arrangements that have been </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">put in place following the fundamental review of our core process and role?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 43.2pt; orphans:0; text-indent:-21.6pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.35pt"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">What </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">control will </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:0.05pt">I </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">have over the quality of service provision?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 14.4pt 0pt 43.2pt; orphans:0; text-indent:-21.6pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.35pt"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">What would be my rights to withdraw from such a service if it wasn't working </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">to my satisfaction and to deliver my strategic aims?</span></p><p style="margin:14.4pt 0pt 0pt 3.6pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:0.05pt">Single PSOE:</span></p><p style="margin:12.6pt 3.6pt 0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">A single PSOE appears, superficially, to be a good thing but, from my point of view, it </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">is another myth that has emerged from the mists of prejudice and assumption. To my knowledge it has never be subjected to what the judges call "nice chemical </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">analysis".</span></p><p style="margin:14.4pt 0pt 0pt 3.6pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">Before I could support this idea I should need to be convinced by:</span></p><p style="margin:14.4pt 0pt 0pt 21.6pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.35pt"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">Clearly set out aims, objectives, and outcomes;</span></p><p style="margin:1.8pt 21.6pt 0pt 43.2pt; orphans:0; text-indent:-21.6pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.35pt"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">A clearly set out, argued rationale as to why it would be an improvement on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">where we are now;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.6pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.35pt"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">A cost-benefit analysis;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.6pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.35pt"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">An options appraisal;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.6pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.35pt"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">An audit of necessary changes to primary legislation;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 39.6pt; orphans:0; text-indent:-18pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.35pt"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">An informed and authoritative assessment of the likelihood of legislative </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">changes and a clear indication of timescales;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 25.2pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">• A comprehensive risk assessment.</span></p><p style="margin:10.8pt 7.2pt 0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">I have had brief conversations with Julie Mellor and Jane Martin about this issue. I have made it clear to both that compelling evidence from the combination of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">above list would be a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:0.05pt">sine qua non </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">of my decision to support or not support the idea </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">of a P</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">SOE. At my last meeting with Julie I made it clear that in the absence of such </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">evidence I would not be able to form a considered view of the concept.</span></p><p style="margin:12.6pt 0pt 0pt 7.2pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:0.05pt">European Directive in Alternative Dispute Resolution (ADR)</span></p><p style="margin:14.4pt 3.6pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-indent:3.6pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:0.05pt">What consideration have you given to the introduction of the Directive and are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:0.05pt">you taking any action in response?</span></p><p style="margin:14.4pt 0pt 0pt 3.6pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:0.05pt">"Appropriate/alternative"</span></p><p style="margin:14.4pt 3.6pt 0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">Although I get the point that the proposal applies to ADR that seeks to resolve </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">disputes between consumers and trade</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">rs "out-of-court" it is a pity that the Directive </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">defines ADR as </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:0.05pt">Alternative </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">Dispute Resolution rather than </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:0.05pt">Appropriate </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">because </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">courts are sometimes the only 'appropriate' forum for the resolution of a dispute </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:0.05pt">(e.g. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">novel points of law, interpretation of t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">he law, where remedies such as damages, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">injunction and specific performance are sought).</span></p><p style="margin:12.6pt 0pt 0pt 3.6pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:0.05pt">Common principles</span></p><p style="margin:14.4pt 3.6pt 0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">The Directive states that effective ADR procedures should be guided by a number of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">common principles, such as impartiality, transparency, effectivene</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">ss, and fairness. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">No ombudsman in the UK or Ireland will disagree with this statement except to say </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">that the criteria set out by the Ombudsman Association (OA) for membership in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">`ombudsman' category might go further than these criteria. The Cabinet off</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">ice and the Ministry of Justice have formally accepted and endorsed OA's extended criteria </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">which are included in their joint guidance to government departments which are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">thinking of reviewing or setting up ombudsman schemes.</span></p><p style="margin:12.6pt 0pt 0pt 3.6pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:0.05pt">Cross-border complaints</span></p><p style="margin:14.4pt 3.6pt 0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">The int</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">ention of the Commission is to propose measures on ADR that ensure that all </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">consumer complaints can be submitted to an ADR entity and that disputes arising from cross-border transactions and the digital environment may be more easily </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">resolved. On the basis</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt"> of past experience, I do not expect my Service to be involved </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">in any cross-border transaction in the terms of the proposal.</span></p><p style="margin:12.6pt 0pt 0pt 3.6pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:0.05pt">Digital environment</span></p><p style="margin:12.6pt 3.6pt 0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">The digital environment is of relevance to my Service and we plan further to develop </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">our website but also to cr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">eate a digital media communication strategy that will help </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">us raise awareness of our services and also to enable easier and wider access to them. We acknowledge government's aspiration to achieve 'digital by default' and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">are seeking to work with others to overcome significant challenges facing residents </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">in my jurisdiction to achieve it. Many, for instance, cannot afford telephone land lines </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">and therefore have no access to broadband and the internet. Many others are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">denied digital facilities by reason of their advanced age, ill-health and other frailty, or </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">special needs.</span></p><p style="margin:10.8pt 3.6pt 0pt 7.2pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">The Directive will require Member States to ensure that all disputes between a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">consumer and a trader arising from the sale of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">goods or the provision of services can </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">be submitted to an ADR entity, including through online means. Subject to the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">challenges referred to above, our new website is designed to be inter-active and, I </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">believe, would already meet the Commission's requiremen</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">t.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:86%; margin:14.4pt 0pt 0pt 3.6pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:0.05pt">Enhanced redress</span></p><p style="margin:14.4pt 3.6pt 0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">The second objective of the Directive to enhance redress for consumers is directly </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">relevant to one of the aspects of my role but I cannot presently see how the Directive </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">will actually enhance redress for residents, landlords, and managing agents in my </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">jurisdiction.</span></p><p style="margin:14.4pt 0pt 0pt 3.6pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:0.05pt">Lack of awareness and uneven quality</span></p><p style="margin:14.4pt 18pt 0pt 3.6pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">The Directive recounts that analysis of the current situation identified certain main </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">shortcomings which hinder the effectiveness of ADR such as the lack of consumer </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">and business awareness, and the uneven quality of ADR procedures.</span></p><p style="margin:12.6pt 10.8pt 0pt 3.6pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">Within the limits placed on us by government in terms of communicating to our customers, we shall continue to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">do all we can raise awareness of our Service. In </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">particular we shall use our new website and will continue to work with landlords and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">their professional and trade bodies and with tenant organisations to get across </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">messages about who we are, what we do, and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt"> how we add value.</span></p><p style="margin:14.4pt 18pt 0pt 3.6pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">I am not in a position to comment on whether there is uneven quality of ADR </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">procedures in the context of rented housing. I can say, however, that the quality of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">my Service has been consistently recognised and reflected in objective and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">u</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">nsolicited evidence.</span></p><p style="margin:12.6pt 0pt 0pt 3.6pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:0.05pt">Residual cross-sectoral entity</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:112%; margin:12.6pt 28.8pt 0pt 3.6pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">Apart from my comments about private-for-profit landlords and managing agents being required to join my Scheme, I presently have no views on a residual cross</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">&#xad;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">sectoral </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">entity.</span></p><p style="margin:10.8pt 0pt 0pt 3.6pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:0.05pt">Complaints filed by traders a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:0.05pt">gainst consumers</span></p><p style="margin:12.6pt 7.2pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-indent:3.6pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">The Commission's proposal covers disputes between consumers and traders (the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">latter being defined as "any natural persons or any legal person, irrespective of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">whether privately or publicly owned, who is acting, including through any person</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">acting in his name or on his behalf, for purposes relating to his trade, business, craft </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">or profession arising from the sale of goods or the provision of services") and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">includes complaints filed by consumers against traders as well as complaints filed by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">traders against consumers. In the context of the Housing Ombudsman and assuming </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">that the definition of "trader" includes landlords, there would have to be a change in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">primary legislation to allow landlords to trigger disputes coming to me.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt 194.4pt 0pt 3.6pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:0.05pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt 194.4pt 0pt 3.6pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:0.05pt">Accessible information about ADR providers </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">The proposal states:</span></p><p style="margin:9pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; orphans:0; text-indent:3.6pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:0.05pt">"When disputes arise, consumers must be able to quickly identify which ADR </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:0.05pt">entities are competent to deal with their dispute. To this end, this proposal </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:0.05pt">ensures that consumers will be able to find information on the competent ADR entity in the main commercial documents provided by the trader and, where a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:0.05pt">trader has a website, on that website. In addition, traders will have to inform </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:0.05pt">consumers on whether or</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:0.05pt"> not they commit to use ADR in relation to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:0.05pt">complaints lodged against them by a consumer. This obligation will act as an </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:0.05pt">incentive for traders to use ADR more frequently."</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:113%; margin:16.2pt 7.2pt 0pt 3.6pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">To the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">extent that "traders" includes landlords in my jurisdiction, these criteria are met. Some landlords even make clear in their tenancy agreements residents' rights </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">to escalate disputes. If for-profit private-sector landlords and managing agents were </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">required</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt"> to join my Scheme as a result of the Directive, I have the power in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">approved Scheme to require the same criteria of them.</span></p><p style="margin:9pt 0pt 0pt 3.6pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:0.05pt">Costs, length, and complexity</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:114%; margin:10.8pt 3.6pt 0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">I am confident that the fundamental changes we have made recently to our </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">procedures and practices i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">ncluding, especially, our re-engineered core dispute </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">resolution process and strategic re-alignment of resources linked to an activity-based </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">costing model will meet the following requirement of the Commission's proposal:</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:113%; margin:10.8pt 32.4pt 0pt 39.6pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:0.05pt">`ADR procedures should be effective </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:0.05pt">and address certain shortcomings </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:0.05pt">associated with court procedures, such as costs, length and complexity."</span></p><p style="margin:9pt 0pt 0pt 3.6pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:0.05pt">Resolution within 90 days</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:114%; margin:12.6pt 7.2pt 0pt 3.6pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">Since we have re-aligned our resources to deliver early local dispute resolution we </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">are completing cases in minutes, days, o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">r weeks and would expect in the majority of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">cases to satisfy the Commission's requirement that:</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:113%; margin:10.8pt 14.4pt 0pt 39.6pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:0.05pt">" Based on the results of existing studies, the present proposal requires that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:0.05pt">disputes should be resolved within 90 days."</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:114%; margin:9pt 18pt 0pt 3.6pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">The addition of the word "generally" later in the text satisfies me that 90 days is a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">desirable rather than an absolute and permits flexibility and discretion to produce a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">just outcome in appropriate cases such as, for instance, novel or complex cases, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">ins</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">tances involving systemic issues, or matters containing important learning </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">outcomes for the sector or in the public interest.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 3.6pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:0.05pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 3.6pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:0.05pt">Free of charge</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:110%; margin:9pt 0pt 0pt 3.6pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">The proposal states that:</span></p><p style="margin:10.8pt 10.8pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-align:right; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:0.05pt">"In order to ensure that ADR procedures remain accessible to all </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:0.05pt">consumers,</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:113%; margin:1.8pt 46.8pt 0pt 39.6pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:0.05pt">the present proposal provides that they should be free of charge or of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:0.05pt">moderate cost for consumers."</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:10.8pt 39.6pt 0pt 3.6pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">The services of my organisation are free to residents at the point of complaint. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:0.05pt">Competent authorities</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:113%; margin:9pt 3.6pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">It is proposed that, in each Member State</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">, a competent authority will be in charge of monitoring the functioning of ADR entities established on its territory. The competent authorities will, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:0.05pt">inter alia, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">assess, on the basis of information notified to them by ADR </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">entities, whether a given ADR enti</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">ty respects the quality requirements laid down by the present proposal.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:114%; margin:9pt 10.8pt 0pt 3.6pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">It is not clear to me how such an arrangement would align with my existing duty </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">under statute to report annually to the Secretary of State who lays the report before </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">Parliament. If it </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">means double reporting there will be an unnecessarily bureaucratic </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">process and a risk that resources that would be better directed to providing an improved service to consumers will be needlessly spent on duplication.</span></p><p style="margin:7.2pt 3.6pt 0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">It seems to me that where reports are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">laid before Parliament they are documents of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">public record and this requirement should be enough to meet the requirements of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">Directive. Equally, the public availability of such reports should be enough to enable:</span></p><p style="margin:10.8pt 3.6pt 0pt 39.6pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:0.05pt">" the competent authorities to publish regular reports on the development and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:0.05pt">functioning of ADR entities. Every three years, the Commission will report to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:0.05pt">the European Parliament and the Council on the application of the Directive".</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:21.6pt 25.2pt 0pt 3.6pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:0.05pt">To what extent do you </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:0.05pt">believe the Directive will allow better and meaningful </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:0.05pt">comparisons in performance and sharing of practice across providers or agencies?</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:9pt 10.8pt 0pt 3.6pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">I do not believe that the Directive will allow better comparisons in performance. Ombudsmen in the UK, for instance, hav</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">e tried in a variety of networking </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:0.05pt">fora </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">make </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">such comparisons but their constitutional arrangements, core processes, and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">related performance measures, or KPIs, or targets are so disparate that comparison </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">inevitably fails to get apples and pears to coinc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">ide.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:114%; margin:9pt 32.4pt 0pt 3.6pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">Subject to my fears of duplication and unnecessary costs referred to above, I do </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">believe, however, that "competent authorities" and the collation of reporting </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">mechanisms by the Commission to the European Parliament will provide the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">potential for a fra</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">mework to facilitate sharing of good practice.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:114%; margin:0pt 14.4pt 0pt 7.2pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:0.05pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:114%; margin:0pt 14.4pt 0pt 7.2pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:0.05pt">To what extent do you think the Directive presents an opportunity to remodel </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:0.05pt">the existing system of ADR to resolve possible existing overlaps, shortfalls, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:0.05pt">and conflicts?</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:114%; margin:9pt 3.6pt 0pt 7.2pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">The Directive states that another of the main shortcomings which hinders the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">effectiveness of ADR is "gaps in the coverage". The most obvious gap in terms of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">my jurisdiction is the fact that the vast majority of consumers of services provided by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">private, f</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">or-profit landlords and managing agents are excluded from access to my </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">Service, and, therefore, justice, in respect of unsatisfactory provision of those </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">services for which they pay market rents. These consumers have for too long been </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">the Cinderellas at the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt"> ADR ball. Government strongly supports the role of the private </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">sector in the provision of rented housing. Giving tenants in this sector the right to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">escalate their disputes to the Housing Ombudsman would not only give them the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">rights of access to ADR requ</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">ired by the Directive and thereby access to out-of-court </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">justice but would also test standards in that sector and drive up the quality of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">customer service by reference to an ever-increasing body of learning arising out of a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">rich bank of ombudsman decision-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">outcomes.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:10.8pt 3.6pt 0pt 7.2pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:0.05pt">How can those involved in dispute resolution, but who aren't covered by the Directive, ensure that they are meeting the same expected standards of quality </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:0.05pt">as those who are covered by it?</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:9pt 3.6pt 0pt 7.2pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">As stated above, Ombudsman members of OA will not have diff</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">iculty meeting the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">standards. Indeed, many of us, no doubt, will be able to argue that we exceed them.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:114%; margin:9pt 14.4pt 0pt 7.2pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">I suspect that the simple answer to this question is that those who are not covered </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">by the Directive should ensure, by amendment and revision if necessar</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">y, that their </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">constitutional arrangements meet the standards. This will be a matter, as may be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">appropriate, for their Boards, councils, regulators, departmental sponsors, industry </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">stakeholders, and, ultimately, government.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:114%; margin:10.8pt 3.6pt 0pt 7.2pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:0.05pt">How can the government ensure aga</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:0.05pt">inst the proliferation of excessive </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:0.05pt">numbers of different dispute resolution bodies and mechanisms (and should it </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:0.05pt">be doing so)?</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:10.8pt 14.4pt 0pt 3.6pt; orphans:0; text-indent:3.6pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">This is definitely something in respect of which the government should be taking a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">lead. The proliferation of different ombudsmen and other dispute resolution bodies </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">in the same or similar industries, sectors, or businesses is very confusing to consumers and does not </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">serve them well in terms of straightforward access to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">justice.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:7.2pt 10.8pt 0pt 3.6pt; orphans:0; text-indent:3.6pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">Governme</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">nt should ensure that the OA guidance endorsed by the Cabinet Office </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">and the Ministry of Justice is followed by its departments. One valuable contribution </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">to this outcome would be that all legislation setting up or reviewing ombudsmen or </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">other ADR schemes </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">should be subject to a pre-condition of approval by Cabinet </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">Office advised by Treasury Solicitors.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 7.2pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:0.05pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 7.2pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:0.05pt">Specific action</span></p><p style="margin:10.8pt 3.6pt 0pt 7.2pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">I have decided not to take any immediate action in response to the Directive </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">principally because I cannot see any obvious impact on my Service particularly in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">context of efforts to "improve the functioning of the retail internal market".</span></p><p style="margin:12.6pt 25.2pt 0pt 7.2pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">For the moment, I have decided to keep in close contact with fellow ombudsmen, especially t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">hose in the private sector, and monitor how the introduction of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">Directive develops and take any action as may be necessary.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:114%; margin:14.4pt 10.8pt 0pt 7.2pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">Given that my Service's mission is "impartial dispute resolution for the whole rented sector", I shall be alert to any opportuni</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">ty afforded by the Directive to argue that the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">whole of the rented housing sector (including the private, for-profit sector) should be included in my jurisdiction.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:111%; margin:9pt 3.6pt 0pt 7.2pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:0.05pt">I </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">hope that this contribution is helpful to you and your Committee. Please contact my office</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt"> if you need any additional information. I should be very happy to meet you at </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">the House of Commons or at my office if you would like to discuss these matters </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">further.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:111%; margin:9pt 3.6pt 0pt 7.2pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:111%; margin:9pt 3.6pt 0pt 7.2pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:0.05pt">November 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>